When working with semantic versioning a.k.a. semver, it&rsquo;s often useful to use range constraints1 to express the versions you&rsquo;re interested in.
The most useful ones are the tilde (~) and the circumflex / hat / caret (^)2:
~4.2.1: picks up 4.2.x for x &gt;= 1 ^5.0.2: picks up 5.x.y for x &gt;= 0 and y &gt;= 2 Popular software tooling that uses them include:
nodejs / npm packages terraform ruby gems (here ~&gt; is used instead of simply ~) Sometimes I use https://jubianchi.github.io/semver-check to double-check3, or to teach teammates how the range constraints work.
Or constraint ranges? ðŸ¤”&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
In Portuguese we say &ldquo;acento circunflexo&rdquo; (circumflex accent). In English, AFAIK, &ldquo;caret&rdquo; is the most precise term however people typically refer to it as &ldquo;hat&rdquo;.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
Example.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

Refer to the previous post about AoC, and to the git repository with my solutions in Python 3.
Link to Day #1 puzzle.
This is just a warm-up.
Given two lists of integers, iterate over them and sum the absolute difference between each pair. zip + sum is the perfect pair1 for the job.
Part two: iterate over the left list whilst accumulating how often the element appears in the right list. &ldquo;How often&rdquo; has, almost always, the smell of a Counter.
The full solution2:
#!/usr/bin/env python3 import sys from collections import Counter def main(): with open(sys.argv[1]) as input: lines = input.read().splitlines() left = [] right = [] for line in lines: l, r = map(int, line.split()) left.append(l) right.append(r) left.sort() right.sort() # part one print(sum(abs(l - r) for (l, r) in zip(left, right))) freqs = Counter(right) # part two print(sum(l * freqs[l] for l in left)) if __name__ == &#39;__main__&#39;: main() I&rsquo;m not sure I like it, And Iâ€˜m so tired of fighting&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
The git repository is ever-evolving and the source of truth, whereas the blog post is a snapshot. I&rsquo;ll experiment with cross-posting solutions here even though it duplicates the repository ones.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

Deeper into the rabbit hole:
% fd Dockerfile.dockerignore | xargs -n 1 rename &#39;s/Dockerfile\.dockerignore/.dockerignore/&#39; The pre-commit identify library currently mistags these files as Dockerfiles, even though they are not1, which creates all sorts of issues.
They are akin to .gitignore files in terms of structure.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

When working with pre-commit.com and specifying language: golang for a given hook, you may want to install dependencies as part of the hook bootstrapping process.
Recently I needed to do so for yq1:
The .pre-commit-config.yaml looked like this:
repos: - repo: local hooks: - id: helm-dirname-must-match-chart-name name: Helm chart directory name must match the chart name files: /Chart\.(yml|yaml)$ entry: ci/helm_check_match_dirname_chart_name.sh language: golang additional_dependencies: - https://github.com/mikefarah/yq Context for the hook and the script: https://stackoverflow.com/q/79166730/1745064.
It didn&rsquo;t work. It&rsquo;s necessary to drop the https:// prefix.
repos: - repo: local hooks: - id: helm-dirname-must-match-chart-name name: Helm chart directory name must match the chart name files: /Chart\.(yml|yaml)$ entry: ci/helm_check_match_dirname_chart_name.sh language: golang additional_dependencies: - github.com/mikefarah/yq That didn&rsquo;t work either. Then I realized I needed to specify an exact version2:
repos: - repo: local hooks: - id: helm-dirname-must-match-chart-name name: Helm chart directory name must match the chart name files: /Chart\.(yml|yaml)$ entry: ci/helm_check_match_dirname_chart_name.sh language: golang additional_dependencies: - github.com/mikefarah/yq@v4.44.3 It also didn&rsquo;t work! There was an error message about the need to specify /v4 in the path for whatever reason:
repos: - repo: local hooks: - id: helm-dirname-must-match-chart-name name: Helm chart directory name must match the chart name files: /Chart\.(yml|yaml)$ entry: ci/helm_check_match_dirname_chart_name.sh language: golang additional_dependencies: - github.com/mikefarah/yq/v4@v4.44.3 That worked! Test it:
pre-commit run --all-files helm-dirname-must-match-chart-name [--verbose] yq is like jq for YAML instead of JSON.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
@latest would also work. However, for the sake of reproducibility, pinning is more reliable.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

At Google we had a prodaccess command used to log in and authenticate in all sorts of internal corp systems1 for 20 hours. It became a daily ritual to run prodaccess first thing in the morning when logging in upon unlocking our physical workstations2.
During the pandemic, when heavily using our virtual workstations (dubbed cloudtops, think of an EC2 instance or a VPS) it was common to hook prodaccess into ssh. There was a prodcertstatus command that would tell you when prodaccess would expire. A common pattern was to modify your ssh startup command to automatically run prodaccess whenever prodcertstatus indicated that access would expire within 2-4 hours, depending on the user&rsquo;s preference.
Given my trained muscle memory, I wanted to continue to use this alias even in environments other than Google:
% cat ~/.profile.d/functions_corp.sh [...] prodaccess() { echo &#34;--&gt; VPN&#34; vpn_login echo &#34;--&gt; Teleport&#34; teleport_login echo &#34;--&gt; AWS&#34; aws_login echo &#34;--&gt; Azure&#34; azure_login case &#34;$1&#34; in -u|--update) echo &#34;--&gt; mr&#34; # Update all well-known corp repositories (cd ~/Corp &amp;&amp; mr update &amp;&amp; mr run git world) # Package manager upgrade echo &#34;--&gt; sd-world&#34; sd-world shift ;; -a|--all) echo &#34;--&gt; Atlas Mongo&#34; atlas_login shift ;; esac } [...] Notes:
mr is https://myrepos.branchable.com/ (&ldquo;a tool to manage all your version control repositories&rdquo;)3 sd-world was introduced in a previous post: it performs a full system upgrade --all holds services I only need / use from time to time. shift is not really needed, but IMHO it&rsquo;s a good practice (and another ingrained habit of mine), especially when inside for loops git world is an alias in my ~/.gitconfig that runs git fetch --all &amp;&amp; git remote prune origin Every morning I invoke prodaccess -u when starting my work day. A few password prompts and touch IDs later and I do not need to worry about logging in anymore during the middle of the day, which reduces overall context switching and stress.
Until someone in CorpEng decided it was a good idea to deprecate it in favour of a new gcert command, destroying many SWE-years of developed muscle memory.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
Ah, the good ol&rsquo; times.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;
I should write a post about it sometime.&#160;&#x21a9;&#xfe0e;

Recipe to list all pods that belong to a given node:
$ kubectl get pod -o wide --field-selector spec.nodeName={node_name} -A Source: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/39231880/kubernetes-api-get-pods-on-specific-nodes
